those\nof 1949 end 1984. the research director of the United Btates\nChamber of Commerce believes.\nDr. Emerson P. Schmidt, basing his appraisal partly on a\nsurvey of trade associations, forecast an unemployment total\n\"possibly topping 5 million.\u201d\nThe word \u201crecession\" wss\nsymposium which heard other\npanelists describe the economy\nes \"sluggish,\" \u201cIn a downturn,\u201d\nor In a \"sidewise movement.\"\nHopeful on Upturn\nDr. Schmidt tempered his\nforthright description of condl\nlions with a hopeful view of an\n1 upturn in the later part of\nnext year. Other panelists gen\nerally took the same position.\nSpokesmen for 14 Industries\nwho participated with Mr\nSchmidt In the symposium\nwere divided, but in general re- j\nfleeted somewhat greater op\ntimism.\nMore than half believed:\ntheir own Industries would 1\nwmmmmmmmK*chuiv oshkosh with Libhhmhmm\nyd\nFulton So Light\nHalf as light as a feather. Aluminum construe\nWon. Zipper or lock closure. Available In blue\nor brown.\nfrom 20.00 plus tax\nChnvy CbnM* Downtown Virgin*#*\nWisconsin and\u2019 1141 Conn. 7 Corners\nWestern Are*. Arenue Shopping Center\n*^**9999\u20146Open Might* Mon. Thru Fri. \u25a0\u25a0BHHBBBBHB\nil Thg item b\u00ablow it an example of HUNDREDS t\nVOF FAMOUS BRANDS IN THIS SALE! Choose From 1/ fc\nBourbons Gins Vodkas Champagnes K\nScotches Rums Ryes Cordials I L!\nain jaa\nBUY 3 BOTTLES j\nat our already low, low shelf price g\n_ BUDGET I\nJg? DISCOUNT g\nr OR BUY A CASE IF YOU WISH\nAND QET A <4.00 DISCOUNT!\ni\\ \u2022nfesSr' Slock up for Christmas and\nI 1 \u2014tm y& at this sensationally low price! E9\nmjmfM tfl New York State I\nHHH CHAMPAGNE g\nri/n 1.99 our low price\n5.97 tor 3 Fifth* I^l\nK, Your Dollar Ditcount fj\nHi \u25a0Wfl/tJ JlihtauJl JM Thu i* ell y\u00abu gey ter 3 LdJ\nbeltlu el Andrt' Dupr*\nThis Sale Applies to Every Bottle in Our Store\nRHF23I2 WISCONSIN\nused during n business outlook\nr\nwind up next year with better\nsales showings than In pros\nperous 1967\u2014though with de\nclining profits In msny cases\nand tougher competition in all\ncases.\ni Blight uptrends were fore\nseen for auto sales, homebulld\nlng. electronics, chemicals/ de\npartment store and food sales,\ni commercial airlines and con\nsumer credit.\nDowntrends, at least In the\ni next sis months, were pre-1\ndieted for most household ap\npliances and consumer dur\nables, furniture and home fur\nnishings. railroads and foreign\ntrade. The basic steel Industry\nwas seen si lagging in the first\nhalf of the year but ending\n1958 lust about even wtih 1867.\nDr. Schmidt said that while\nthe 1989 recession ia likely to\nbe at leaat as severe as In 1949\nand 1964, with unemployment\nbetween 5 and per cent, the\nbasic forces making for eco\nnomic expansion in the lont\nrun are as strong as ever and\nare likely to help prevent any\nmajor collapse,\nDr. Schmidt explained,\n\"many of the essential read\njustments have already been\nmade. There Is a possibility\nthat before 1958 closes, ex\npansionist forces will again ex\nceed contractive forces which\nare now clearly visible.\"\nHe added thst he foresee# no\nlikelihood of s \u201creal forward\nthrust\" in the first six months.\nHarry A Bullls, board chair\nman of General Mills, Inc., saw\nthe present \"business slump\"\nas probably of \"limited dura\ntion.\u201d He la chairman of the\nchamber's Economic Policy\nCommittee.\n\u201cBoom Is Over\u201d\nThe boom is over, Mr. Bullls\nsaid bluntly. He called for bold\ni plans to meet the double crisis\n\u201ctypified by the Sputnik and\nthe threat of an economic re\ncession.\u201d\nHe opened the door to a\nconsideration of deficit spend\ning by the Government, saying:\n\u201cA balanced budget Is highly\ndesirable, but It should not be\na fetish If national security\nbe threatened thereby, or eco\nnomic growth Inhibited.\"\nHe did not. however, rule out\nthe possibility of a tax cut. As\nsoon ss (he need for additional\noutlays for missiles is deter\nmined. he explained, it shall be\npossible also to determine\nwhether there Is to be a budget\nIncrease for defense or a budget\nreduction with a tax cut. Either\npolicy, or a combination of the\ntwo. would stimulate the econo\nmy, he predicted.\nHighlights of Statements\nHere are highlights of state\nments by those who predicted\nbetter business:\nAutomobiles\u2014New car sales\nare expected to total 8.1 to 8.2\nmillion, or slightly more than\nIn 1957. Higher prices do not\nappear to have too much dam\npening effect on demand. Deal\ners are experiencing a cost\nprofit squeeze.\nTelevision and radio\u2014About\n6.5 million TV sets made and\nsold this year and the industry\n\u25a0\u25a0k je JB\n...V\n--ff- M\nCONVICTED OF LARCENY\u2014Dave Beck,\npresident of the Teamsters Union, smiles\non leaving courthouse where a Seattle jury\nlater found him guilty of stealing $1,900 from\nthe sale of a union-owned Cadillac.\u2014AP Wire\nphoto.\nexpects this figure to rise to 7\nmillion or more In 1955. The\nradio segment of the Industry\n,1s experiencing a boom. Factory\nsales of all electronics, amount- 1\ning to more than 87 billion in\n1967. are expected to increase i\nby 8 to 10 per cent In 1958\nMilitary procurement led the\n1987 increase.\nHome building Starts of\nprivate homes. *a little under 1\nmillion this year, are expected\nto be about 1 million next year\nPerhaps there will be a small\nincrease in price.\nMortgage Credit to Rise\nMortgage financing\u2014Assum\ning a moderate easing of credit\nby the Federal Reserve Board\nthe supply of mortgage credit\nshould total 826 5 billion This\nwould be about 82 billion, or 8\nper cent, above 1957.\nOeneral contracting An\nother good year with volume of\nconstruction put la, place up\nabout 4 per cent to 849 billion.\nFood stores\u2014A 5.3 per cent\nrise In total food sales pre\ndicted. With the 1957 total\nrunning at about S4B billion j\nthis would mean a total of\nabout 850.5 billion. Food chains\nplan to build 2,000 supermar\nkets and remodel 1.700 existing\nones at a cost of 8635 million\nDepartment and specialty l\nstores\u2014About the same sales 1\nvolume Is seen for 1958 and in\n1967. Unless the tendency of i\nbuyers to \"tighten their purse i\nj\nhoi t/w6e u>e j\nEau de Colognes Porfumos\nCombination Sets\nThe complete 4711 line from bo* J\nto boudoir offer* something special\nt *!sSnP* M or och m,f,ib r y\u00b0 ur ,omi| y'\nthe your friends.\nw Priced from J\nI'M*\u00aellloo J\nImported from Cologne, the City of 4711 feme\n\u2022esit* coiooni on mmiiA sviiit IB\n*\u00a5\u00a5^J^\u00ae5 e\nstrings,\" coupled with the gen\neral business slump, is reversed\nthere Is little likelihood of a\nsharp rise In retail sales In the\nspring. Prices are seen as un\nchanged to 1 per cent up in\n1958.\nMore Consumer Credit\nConsumer finance\u2014About a\n10 per cent increase in con\nsumer credit looked for.\nSteel\u2014Production for 1958\nestimated at 115 to 116 million\nnet tons against 114 million\nthis year.\nChemicals\u2014A 5 per cent rise\nto a total of 825 billion pro\nduction and probably \u201csome\nselective price increases.\u201d\nThe trucking industry was\ndescribed as \"guardedly opti\nmistic\" about 1958. The rail\nroads were frankly pessimistic.\nBail traffic in 1958. both freight\nand passenger, was foreseen as\n5 per cent under 1957, which is\nadded to the 1957 slump from\n1956. Net income of the rails\nafter fixed charges was esti\nmated at about 8600 million in\n1858. or 20 per cent under 1957.\nAir transport Is faced with\nja profit squeeze, with travel\nup but fares held down, and\nthe Industry facing the crucial\nproblem of conversion to jets.\nIn foreign trade a 5 per cent\ndrop In commercial exports was i\npredicted, with a alight drop in\nimports. i\nBeck Convided\nOs $1,900 Theft\nIn Auto Sale\nContinued From First Page\nbeen notified the younger Beck*\nconviction will be appealed.\nIndicted Last Bummer\nThe Teamster chief and his\nson were indicted last summer\nby a King County Grand Jury\nwhich was called after Beck\ninvoked the Fifth Amendment\nmore than 100 times before the\nSenate Rackets Investigating\nCommittee.\nThe Senate hearing, early in\nthe year, delved deeply Into\nBeck\u2019s handling of Teamster\nfunds. Senator MoClellan,\nDemocrat of Arkansas, the\nchairman, accused Beck at the\nend of having misappropriated\nmore than 8300,000 of Team\nster money for his own use.\nAt the grand larceny trial,\nthe state based ita case oo the\nuncontested fact that the gl.Boo\nhad been deposited in the ac\ncount of the Beck-owned BAB\nInvestment Co., and bank rec\nords showed there had been no\nwithdrawals for that amount.\nBeck, hlmaelf, acknowledged\nthat the 1952 Cadillac had been\nfor hla personal use, that he\nauthorised Its sale to a beer\ntruck driver and kdew the\nmoney had gone Into the B A B\naccount. But he said the trans\naction on January 30.1858, was\nhandled by his secretary during\nhla absence from the city. The\nsecretary backed up this latter\nstatement.\nContribution Claimed\nLater In his dramatic final\narguments. Mr. Burdell told\nthe jury the 81,900 had been\nturned over by Beck to a politi\ncal friend aa a campaign con\ntribution on behalf of the\nWestern Conference of Team\nsters, which bought the Cadil\nlac.\nMr. Burdell said the reason\nthis had not been brought out\nin direct testimony was that\nBeck would never put himself\nInto the position of having to\n\"finger\u201d anyone by telling who\ngot the money.\nThe State contended\u2014and\nthe jurors believed\u2014that the\n81.900 had been deliberately\nentered in the books with in\ntent to defraud and had been\nhidden as an entry of income\nfrom a real estate sale.\nBeck, beset on many sides\nsince the Senate hearings,\nradiated a jaunty sir of self\nconfidence during his tribula\ntions He shed more than 20\npounds during the year, but\nsaid it was Intentional.\nToday, however, hla good\nhumor wss gone.\nThe conviction wss another\nstep down what his own law\nyer described as a \u201cwaning\ncareer.\u201d","height":"28877","width":"18465"}}
